<h2><a name="atof" id="atof">atof</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>
Syntax:
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;cstdlib&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">double</span> atof<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">const</span> <span class="kw4">char</span> <span class="sy0">*</span>str <span class="br0">&#41;</span>;</pre>
<p>

The function atof() converts str into a double, then returns that value. str
must start with a valid number, but can be terminated with any non-numerical
character, other than “E” or “e”. For example,
</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">     x <span class="sy0">=</span> atof<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="st0">&quot;42.0 is the answer&quot;</span> <span class="br0">&#41;</span>;</pre>
<p>

results in x being set to 42.0.
</p>

<p>
